## Java Solution

```java id="jlwm0c"
class Solution {

    List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<Integer> preorderTraversal(TreeNode root) {

        preorder(root);

        return ans;
    }

    public void preorder(TreeNode root){

        if(root == null)
            return;

        ans.add(root.val);

        preorder(root.left);

        preorder(root.right);
    }
}
```

---

## Recursion Flow

Consider the tree:

```text id="jlwm0d"
        1
       / \
      2   3
```

Function calls happen like this:

```text id="jlwm0e"
preorder(1)

│
├── Visit 1
│
├── preorder(2)
│      ├── Visit 2
│      ├── preorder(null)
│      └── preorder(null)
│
└── preorder(3)
       ├── Visit 3
       ├── preorder(null)
       └── preorder(null)
```

Every recursive call performs the **same three steps**:

1. Visit current node.
2. Traverse left.
3. Traverse right.

---

## Complexity Analysis

| Operation             | Time Complexity |
| --------------------- | --------------- |
| Visit every node once | O(n)            |

**Time Complexity:** `O(n)`

Reason:

* Every node is visited exactly once.

---

**Space Complexity:** `O(h)`

Where `h` is the height of the tree.

* Balanced Tree:

```text id="jlwm0f"
O(log n)
```

* Skewed Tree:

```text id="jlwm0g"
O(n)
```

The extra space is used by the recursion call stack.

---

## Key Learning

* Preorder follows:

```text id="jlwm0h"
Node → Left → Right
```

* Visit the current node **before** visiting its children.
* Recursion naturally handles traversing each subtree.
* The base case is when the current node becomes `null`.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Forgetting the base case.

Always write:

```java id="jlwm0i"
if(root == null)
    return;
```

Otherwise, recursion will continue indefinitely.

---

❌ Visiting the node after the recursive calls.

For preorder, always visit first:

```java id="jlwm0j"
ans.add(root.val);

preorder(root.left);

preorder(root.right);
```

Changing the order changes the traversal type.

---

❌ Forgetting to initialize the answer list.

Always create:

```java id="jlwm0k"
List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
```

to store the traversal result.

---

## Pattern Recognition

Whenever a problem asks for:

* Preorder Traversal
* Root before children
* Copying or serializing a tree
* DFS where the parent must be processed first

Think:

```text id="jlwm0l"
Preorder DFS
```

Rule:

```text id="jlwm0m"
Node

↓

Left

↓

Right
```

---

## Difference Between DFS Traversals

| Traversal | Order               |
| --------- | ------------------- |
| Preorder  | Node → Left → Right |
| Inorder   | Left → Node → Right |
| Postorder | Left → Right → Node |

The only difference is **where you process (visit) the current node**.

---

## Takeaway

The key idea of Preorder Traversal is to **process the current node before exploring its children**. Using recursion, every subtree is treated as a smaller binary tree that follows the same **Node → Left → Right** pattern. This makes the solution simple, elegant, and runs in **O(n)** time.
